@page "/facility"

<section class="facility-hero">
    <h1>Our Facility (Conceptual Model)</h1>
    <p>
        Ripple’s facility, as presented in this college honors project, is a hypothetical 
        year‑round indoor aquaponics space designed to illustrate how sustainable food production 
        could operate in an urban environment. While no physical facility exists, this model 
        demonstrates how efficiency, food safety, research, and community involvement could be 
        integrated into a real system.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="facility-section">
    <h2>Facility Layout</h2>
    <p>
        The conceptual warehouse is divided into three main areas to show how a real aquaponics 
        nonprofit might organize its space:
    </p>

    <div class="facility-grid">
        <div class="facility-card">
            <h3>Food Production (70%)</h3>
            <p>
                This section models the core of the system: tilapia tanks, filtration and 
                biofiltration systems, nutrient‑rich water circulation, multi‑level hydroponic 
                channels, and LED grow lighting. These components reflect real aquaponic practices 
                but are used here for demonstration only.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="facility-card">
            <h3>Research Area (15%)</h3>
            <p>
                A conceptual space dedicated to testing new aquaponic configurations, monitoring 
                water quality, experimenting with plant varieties, and improving system efficiency. 
                This area highlights the role research could play in a real implementation.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="facility-card">
            <h3>Community Garden & Education (15%)</h3>
            <p>
                This modeled area shows how community members, students, and volunteers could learn 
                aquaponics hands‑on. It represents the educational and outreach potential of a 
                real facility, even though no such space currently exists.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="facility-section">
    <h2>Biosecurity & Food Safety (Modeled)</h2>
    <p>
        The project describes a facility with separate zones for fish, plants, and packaging, 
        strict wash‑in/wash‑out procedures, daily water checks, and automated sensors for pH, 
        temperature, ammonia, and nitrate. These practices reflect real‑world standards but are 
        included here as part of the conceptual design.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="facility-section">
    <h2>How the System Works</h2>
    <p>
        Ripple’s modeled system uses a <strong>decoupled aquaponics design</strong>, where fish and 
        plant systems can be adjusted independently. This approach allows for better water control, 
        easier harvesting, reduced stress on fish, and more stable plant growth — all presented as 
        part of the academic exploration.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="facility-section">
    <h2>Designed for Sustainability</h2>
    <p>
        The conceptual facility incorporates skylights, efficient LED lighting, water recirculation, 
        minimal chemical inputs, and a layout designed for long‑term scalability. These features 
        demonstrate how a real aquaponics facility could prioritize environmental responsibility.
    </p>
</section>
